{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XApuuotBSc3JR4uN5bXtwa","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Compute Shader Optimization: Dense Cluster Performance\n     2→\n     3→## Objective\n     4→Maximize boid count at 60 FPS when boids are clustered (worst case).\n     5→Current baseline: **291,000 boids** (browser-measured, clustered steady state).\n     6→\n     7→## The Loop\n     8→1. Read `shader.wgsl` and `simulation.js`\n     9→2. Pick ONE compute optimization\n    10→3. Edit the file(s)\n    11→4. `git add shader.wgsl simulation.js && git commit -m \"experiment: <description>\"`\n    12→5. Run: `python3 evaluate.py`\n    13→6. Parse the last line for `max_boids: NNNNN`\n    14→7. If max_boids > previous best → KEEP, append to `results_perf.tsv`\n    15→8. If max_boids ≤ previous best → `git revert --no-edit HEAD`, append to `results_perf.tsv`\n    16→9. REPEAT. Do NOT pause. Loop until interrupted.\n    17→\n    18→## What You Can Edit\n    19→- `shader.wgsl` — compute kernels, especially `flock_radius`\n    20→- `simulation.js` — grid sizing, buffer layout, pipeline config\n    21→\n    22→## What You CANNOT Edit\n    23→- `bench_browser.js`, `evaluate.py`, `render.wgsl`, `renderer.js`, `index.html`\n    24→- `dashboard.py`, `serve.py`, `program.md`\n    25→- Do NOT add roost attractors or global orbit forces\n    26→\n    27→## CRITICAL: Use `git revert --no-edit HEAD` to undo. NOT `git reset --hard`.\n    28→## Results go in `results_perf.tsv`\n    29→\n    30→## The Problem\n    31→When boids cluster, cells become dense. At 50+ boids/cell × 27 cells = 1350+\n    32→distance checks per boid, with random memory access to boids_src[].\n    33→\n    34→## Research-Backed Optimization Ideas (priority order)\n    35→\n    36→### 1. Read from sorted order (HIGHEST IMPACT)\n    37→The scatter pass already sorts boid indices by cell into `sorted_indices[]`.\n    38→But flock_radius reads `boids_src[other_idx]` — random access across global memory.\n    39→Instead, read neighbor data from a SORTED buffer where particles in the same cell\n    40→are contiguous. This dramatically improves cache coherence.\n    41→Implementation: After scatter, copy boid data into cell-sorted order. Then flock\n    42→reads neighbors from the sorted buffer sequentially.\n    43→\n    44→### 2. Reduce per-boid output writes\n    45→The agent already removed expensive viz-only outputs (experiment 44). Check if\n    46→there are more: dir_change, flock_alignment, sep_pressure, density calculations\n    47→that can be skipped or simplified.\n    48→\n    49→### 3. Hard neighbor cap at 8\n    50→With sorted/cached reads, a lower neighbor cap becomes viable because the\n    51→iteration itself is cheaper. Try capping at 6-8 instead of 16.\n    52→\n    53→### 4. Grid cell size tuning\n    54→Current: `cbrt(numBoids/4)` with worldSize = sphereRadius * 2.5.\n    55→Try: make cellSize = visualRange (so 3x3x3 covers exactly the interaction range).\n    56→This means gridSize = worldSize / visualRange.\n    57→\n    58→### 5. Merge clear_grid + assign_cells\n    59→Each boid can clear its own target cell before writing. Saves one full dispatch.\n    60→\n    61→### 6. Simplify the turn rate limiter further\n    62→Current: normalize + mix + clamp chain. Try: just lerp velocity directly\n    63→without the direction/speed decomposition.\n    64→\n    65→### 7. Reduce visual range when dense\n    66→If a boid finds 8+ neighbors quickly, it doesn't need the full visual range.\n    67→Early-exit the cell loop after finding enough neighbors.\n    68→\n    69→### 8. Use workgroup shared memory for cell data\n    70→Load particles from a cell into workgroup shared memory (var<workgroup>),\n    71→then all threads in the workgroup read from shared mem instead of global.\n    72→Only helps if multiple boids in the workgroup are in the same/adjacent cells.\n    73→\n    74→## New Idea from Research: Branchless Neighbor Accumulation\n    75→Replace branching in the inner loop:\n    76→```wgsl\n    77→// BAD (warp divergence):\n    78→if (d2 < params.visual_range_sq) { ali += other.vel; n_align++; }\n    79→\n    80→// GOOD (all threads compute, mask result):\n    81→let in_range = f32(d2 < params.visual_range_sq && d2 > 0.0001);\n    82→ali += other.vel * in_range;\n    83→coh += other_pos * in_range;\n    84→n_align += u32(in_range);\n    85→let in_sep = f32(d2 < params.separation_dist_sq) * in_range;\n    86→sep += diff * (1.0 - d2 / params.separation_dist_sq) * in_sep;\n    87→```\n    88→This eliminates branch divergence in dense cells where some threads find neighbors and others don't.\n    89→\n    90→## Also Try: Tighter grid cell = visual range\n    91→Set cellSize = visualRange so 3x3x3 search exactly covers the interaction radius.\n    92→gridSize = floor(worldSize / visualRange). No wasted empty cells.\n    93→\n    94→## Note\n    95→291k boids in 3D with 27-cell neighbor search is already competitive with published\n    96→demos. Most \"million boid\" demos are 2D. In 3D, 500k at 60fps is approximately\n    97→the ceiling for uniform grid + spatial hashing on consumer GPUs.\n    98→\n    99→## Constraints\n   100→- flock_radius must produce correct flocking (separation, alignment, cohesion)\n   101→- Boid struct: 64 bytes (16 floats) — don't change the layout\n   102→- Billboard additive + radius neighbor mode is what's benchmarked\n   103→- Benchmark runs in real browser with 30s warmup for clustering\n   104→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9036d8f4-067e-45b6-b2b3-1c0500e3d4cd","uuid":"db39b85e-4a19-40ce-8141-072937726cd7","timestamp":"2026-03-24T02:19:49.792Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/aaronlemke/AI/Murmuration/program.md","content":"# Compute Shader Optimization: Dense Cluster Performance\n\n## Objective\nMaximize boid count at 60 FPS when boids are clustered (worst case).\nCurrent baseline: **291,000 boids** (browser-measured, clustered steady state).\n\n## The Loop\n1. Read `shader.wgsl` and `simulation.js`\n2. Pick ONE compute optimization\n3. Edit the file(s)\n4. `git add shader.wgsl simulation.js && git commit -m \"experiment: <description>\"`\n5. Run: `python3 evaluate.py`\n6. Parse the last line for `max_boids: NNNNN`\n7. If max_boids > previous best → KEEP, append to `results_perf.tsv`\n8. If max_boids ≤ previous best → `git revert --no-edit HEAD`, append to `results_perf.tsv`\n9. REPEAT. Do NOT pause. Loop until interrupted.\n\n## What You Can Edit\n- `shader.wgsl` — compute kernels, especially `flock_radius`\n- `simulation.js` — grid sizing, buffer layout, pipeline config\n\n## What You CANNOT Edit\n- `bench_browser.js`, `evaluate.py`, `render.wgsl`, `renderer.js`, `index.html`\n- `dashboard.py`, `serve.py`, `program.md`\n- Do NOT add roost attractors or global orbit forces\n\n## CRITICAL: Use `git revert --no-edit HEAD` to undo. NOT `git reset --hard`.\n## Results go in `results_perf.tsv`\n\n## The Problem\nWhen boids cluster, cells become dense. At 50+ boids/cell × 27 cells = 1350+\ndistance checks per boid, with random memory access to boids_src[].\n\n## Research-Backed Optimization Ideas (priority order)\n\n### 1. Read from sorted order (HIGHEST IMPACT)\nThe scatter pass already sorts boid indices by cell into `sorted_indices[]`.\nBut flock_radius reads `boids_src[other_idx]` — random access across global memory.\nInstead, read neighbor data from a SORTED buffer where particles in the same cell\nare contiguous. This dramatically improves cache coherence.\nImplementation: After scatter, copy boid data into cell-sorted order. Then flock\nreads neighbors from the sorted buffer sequentially.\n\n### 2. Reduce per-boid output writes\nThe agent already removed expensive viz-only outputs (experiment 44). Check if\nthere are more: dir_change, flock_alignment, sep_pressure, density calculations\nthat can be skipped or simplified.\n\n### 3. Hard neighbor cap at 8\nWith sorted/cached reads, a lower neighbor cap becomes viable because the\niteration itself is cheaper. Try capping at 6-8 instead of 16.\n\n### 4. Grid cell size tuning\nCurrent: `cbrt(numBoids/4)` with worldSize = sphereRadius * 2.5.\nTry: make cellSize = visualRange (so 3x3x3 covers exactly the interaction range).\nThis means gridSize = worldSize / visualRange.\n\n### 5. Merge clear_grid + assign_cells\nEach boid can clear its own target cell before writing. Saves one full dispatch.\n\n### 6. Simplify the turn rate limiter further\nCurrent: normalize + mix + clamp chain. Try: just lerp velocity directly\nwithout the direction/speed decomposition.\n\n### 7. Reduce visual range when dense\nIf a boid finds 8+ neighbors quickly, it doesn't need the full visual range.\nEarly-exit the cell loop after finding enough neighbors.\n\n### 8. Use workgroup shared memory for cell data\nLoad particles from a cell into workgroup shared memory (var<workgroup>),\nthen all threads in the workgroup read from shared mem instead of global.\nOnly helps if multiple boids in the workgroup are in the same/adjacent cells.\n\n## New Idea from Research: Branchless Neighbor Accumulation\nReplace branching in the inner loop:\n```wgsl\n// BAD (warp divergence):\nif (d2 < params.visual_range_sq) { ali += other.vel; n_align++; }\n\n// GOOD (all threads compute, mask result):\nlet in_range = f32(d2 < params.visual_range_sq && d2 > 0.0001);\nali += other.vel * in_range;\ncoh += other_pos * in_range;\nn_align += u32(in_range);\nlet in_sep = f32(d2 < params.separation_dist_sq) * in_range;\nsep += diff * (1.0 - d2 / params.separation_dist_sq) * in_sep;\n```\nThis eliminates branch divergence in dense cells where some threads find neighbors and others don't.\n\n## Also Try: Tighter grid cell = visual range\nSet cellSize = visualRange so 3x3x3 search exactly covers the interaction radius.\ngridSize = floor(worldSize / visualRange). No wasted empty cells.\n\n## Note\n291k boids in 3D with 27-cell neighbor search is already competitive with published\ndemos. Most \"million boid\" demos are 2D. In 3D, 500k at 60fps is approximately\nthe ceiling for uniform grid + spatial hashing on consumer GPUs.\n\n## Constraints\n- flock_radius must produce correct flocking (separation, alignment, cohesion)\n- Boid struct: 64 bytes (16 floats) — don't change the layout\n- Billboard additive + radius neighbor mode is what's benchmarked\n- Benchmark runs in real browser with 30s warmup for clustering\n","numLines":104,"startLine":1,"totalLines":104}}}
