iments with this inverse square root optimization showed only marginal improvements. Writing the struct at once...\n\nI'm wondering if WGSL will actually optimize this differently than individual field writes, or if the GPU coalesces them anyway. The real bottleneck is probably the inner loop's random memory access patterns—reading from sorted indices sequentially is fine, but then jumping around to fetch pos and vel from different boids is where cache misses hurt.\n\nI could create separate sorted buffers just for positions and velocities to keep memory bandwidth tight, since we're only reading those fields anyway. That means adding new buffers and updating the scatter pass to copy data there, but I can modify simulation.js so it's worth exploring.\n\nActually, I could consolidate this into a single sorted_boids buffer where the scatter pass writes complete boid structs in cell order, then flock_radius reads sequentially from that instead of jumping around in the original buffer. The tradeoff is doubling memory usage for boids, but let me first check if a simpler optimization like reusing inverseSqrt calculations makes a measurable difference on my machine before committing to the larger refactor.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":945,"cache_read_input_tokens":55344,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":945},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9036d8f4-067e-45b6-b2b3-1c0500e3d4cd","uuid":"14f97ccf-d8fb-40ef-8cd0-fc6a8e2eee16"}
