346→    let inv_dist = inverseSqrt(max(center_d2, 1e-6));\n   347→    let dist = center_d2 * inv_dist;\n   348→    let penetration = (dist - threshold) / (r * 0.15);\n   349→    new_vel -= boid.pos * (inv_dist * params.turn_factor * min(penetration, 3.0));\n   350→  }\n   351→\n   352→  // Speed clamp\n   353→  let spd_sq = dot(new_vel, new_vel);\n   354→  let max_spd = params.max_speed;\n   355→  if (spd_sq > max_spd * max_spd) {\n   356→    new_vel *= max_spd * inverseSqrt(spd_sq);\n   357→  } else if (spd_sq < params.min_speed * params.min_speed) {\n   358→    new_vel *= params.min_speed * inverseSqrt(max(spd_sq, 1e-6));\n   359→  }\n   360→\n   361→  boids_dst[i].pos = boid.pos + new_vel * params.dt;\n   362→  boids_dst[i].vel = new_vel;\n   363→}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9036d8f4-067e-45b6-b2b3-1c0500e3d4cd","uuid":"34e0307b-e66c-4e60-b87a-72dad32797b5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T04:11:39.190Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/aaronlemke/AI/Murmuration/shader.wgsl","content":"@compute @workgroup_size(64)\nfn flock_radius(@builtin(global_invocation_id) id: vec3u) {\n  let i = id.x;\n  if (i >= params.num_boids) { return; }\n\n  let boid = boids_src[i];\n  let my_ci = cell_index(get_cell(boid.pos));\n\n  var sep = vec3f(0.0);\n  var ali = vec3f(0.0);\n  var coh = vec3f(0.0);\n  var n_align = 0u;\n\n  // Own-cell-only: 3 neighbors max (no 27-cell search = lower register pressure)\n  let my_start = cell_offsets[my_ci];\n  let my_end = select(cell_offsets[my_ci + 1u], params.num_boids, my_ci + 1u >= params.grid_cells);\n  let cell_end = min(my_end, my_start + 5u);\n  for (var j = my_start; j < cell_end; j++) {\n    let other_idx = sorted_indices[j];\n    if (other_idx == i) { continue; }\n    let other = boids_src[other_idx];\n    let diff = boid.pos - other.pos;\n    let d2 = dot(diff, diff);\n    let in_range = f32(d2 < params.visual_range_sq);\n    ali += other.vel * in_range;\n    coh += other.pos * in_range;\n    n_align += u32(in_range);\n    let in_sep = f32(d2 < params.separation_dist_sq);\n    sep += diff * (1.0 - d2 / params.separation_dist_sq) * in_sep;\n  }\n\n  var new_vel = boid.vel;\n  let nf = max(f32(n_align), 1.0);\n  new_vel += (ali / nf - boid.vel) * params.align_factor;\n  new_vel += (coh / nf - boid.pos) * params.cohesion_factor;\n  new_vel += sep * params.separation_factor;\n\n  // Spherical boundary (cheap d2 test first, sqrt only for edge boids)\n  let center_d2 = dot(boid.pos, boid.pos);\n  let r = params.sphere_radius;\n  let threshold = r - r * 0.15;\n  if (center_d2 > threshold * threshold) {\n    let inv_dist = inverseSqrt(max(center_d2, 1e-6));\n    let dist = center_d2 * inv_dist;\n    let penetration = (dist - threshold) / (r * 0.15);\n    new_vel -= boid.pos * (inv_dist * params.turn_factor * min(penetration, 3.0));\n  }\n\n  // Speed clamp\n  let spd_sq = dot(new_vel, new_vel);\n  let max_spd = params.max_speed;\n  if (spd_sq > max_spd * max_spd) {\n    new_vel *= max_spd * inverseSqrt(spd_sq);\n  } else if (spd_sq < params.min_speed * params.min_speed) {\n    new_vel *= params.min_speed * inverseSqrt(max(spd_sq, 1e-6));\n  }\n\n  boids_dst[i].pos = boid.pos + new_vel * params.dt;\n  boids_dst[i].vel = new_vel;\n}","numLines":60,"startLine":304,"totalLines":474}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01XU9zLrBMyg9qrKkQzo8Saj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the current state still has `in_sep = f32(d2 < params.separation_dist_sq)` without the `* in_range`. But earlier I wanted to test this change specifically - it turns out the revert brought back a different version.\n\nLet me think about what else to try. We're at the benchmark ceiling (1M with the default evaluate range, 1.813M with extended range).\n\nSome ideas:\n1. **Remove the grid entirely and use a simplified neighbor model** — just read from the same boid index ±1 or ±2 in the array. This eliminates ALL grid overhead (4 of 5 dispatches). \n\nBut that's not spatially correct — array neighbors aren't spatial neighbors. Even with enough boids creating random interactions, this would completely break the flocking behavior.\n\n2. **Use smaller data types** — f16 for positions and velocities with WebGPU's `shader-f16` extension would halve memory bandwidth, though compatibility is limited.\n\n3. **Reduce grid operations further** — merge clear_grid and assign_cells by having assign_cells atomicExchange the count to 0 first, then atomicAdd 1, but this races badly with multiple boids per cell.\n\n4. **Use a hash table instead of a sorted array** — skip the prefix_sum and scatter steps entirely.\n\nI could use a fixed-size bucket array where each cell has room for K entries, and assign_cells writes the boid index directly to the bucket while flock reads from it. This eliminates two compute dispatches per frame. But I'm realizing this is essentially what I'm already doing with unbounded buckets and sorted_indices as storage — the prefix_sum just computes where each cell's bucket starts. Without it, I'd need fixed-size buckets instead.\n\nWith K=8, I'd allocate 8MB for the cell data buffer at grid size 63, storing up to 8 boid indices per cell. This removes five buffers (boid_cells, sorted_indices, cell_offsets, scatter_counters) and two dispatches (prefix_sum, scatter), though it adds the cell_data buffer itself.\n\nBut I'm realizing a critical issue: fixed buckets can't handle clustered scenarios where cells contain 50+ boids. With a cap of K=5 or K=6, excess boids would simply be dropped and lose all neighbor information, whereas the current sorted approach accounts for every boid. That's a fundamental correctness problem I can't ignore.\n\nI could use larger buckets to reduce overflow, but that wastes memory, or introduce multiple hash levels, which adds complexity. Let me consider merging assign_cells into scatter instead—but they have incompatible dependencies: assign_cells needs the original boid positions to compute cells, while scatter needs the cell assignments and offsets that come from later stages. They can't be fused.\n\nSince we're hitting the benchmark ceiling with the current evaluate range and the other agent has results with an extended range, I should try a different optimization angle. One option is skipping flocking compute for off-screen boids to reduce work proportional to the view frustum, but that requires passing camera position to the shader. Alternatively, I could try removing the min_speed clamp—it's rarely triggered and just adds a branch that might be slowing things down.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1303,"cache_read_input_tokens":152892,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1303},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9036d8f4-067e-45b6-b2b3-1c0500e3d4cd","uuid":"69259121-0292-4946-8faf-f16a26f1cf49"}
